@Adam_Garratt I once read that if you add tomato to a Cottage Pie it becomes a London Pie. Your recipe is so similar to mine that we could probably each claim to have had it stolen! Although I tend to use mixed herbs for Cottage Pie and Thyme for Shepherds. I have to confess that I have always used good quality mince, though I am tempted to try the shin. What cut of lamb would you use for Shepherds pie? As a child, my mother used to mince up left over roast beef and onion - now that was tasty! I also tend to boil the carrots and celery for about 2-3 minutes in the minimum of unsalted water before adding them to the frying onions. The boiling liquor is then reduced a little if there is too much for the stock - it is surprising just how much flavour goes into the water! One trick I have found for getting a good topping (apart from allowing the mixture to go cold which I also have found to be a must) is to just put a ring of potato around the edge and push it hard against the dish (with a knife) which usually stops or at least significantly reduces leakage at the edge (the main culprit for messing up the oven tray I put it on), and then fill the centre and press that down well. As for the top, I tend to use a fork to create an effect like a ploughed field which not only consolidates the top, it gives lots of nice crispy bits. If I have time (usually the case) I do a kind of basket weave pattern on the top - doesn't taste any better, but looks good, especially if you serve it in individual dishes. Regardless of the pattern I always do a single 'ploughed' ring with a fork around the edge.
